Indeed: a look at the paper by @gongenhao suggests that they might not be using adversarial loss for this problem.

This does, however, require we have the target space well modeled. Why robustness to device/protocol variation, if that's the intent, is so important. \2 ... At your current rate of progress, I'm guessing this will probably be a two-linear in fastAI by end of next year.
Right. Using a loss that not only concerns itself with the magnitude of the prediction, but further accounts for the statistical plausibility is quite powerful. \1
It's not just GANs FYI. Other loss functions can have similar behavior

People are still wringing their hands about model based reconstruction in CT - what is real, what is algorithm. So this important topic is hardly confined to ML/AI derived restoration/filtering functions.

The real question, in my mind, isn't if the process works (seems very plausible), only the extent to which it can operate over variation in devices and protocol if it is intended to be general purpose. 2\

I'm guessing it's simply that they use adversarial loss (or a combination thereof) - better suited for image restoration than the usual L2 for regression, which blurs. The point about PET's low-res is key (easy to model the generator) 1\

OK & reasonable - but presence of artifacts in CT/MRI did not preclude FDA approval. In fact will be a great area for radiologists to participate in describing & disseminating these artifacts! Cc: @DrGMcGinty

That's the exactly the issue, radiologists have experience with low-dose, motion, amd missing contrast-agent 'artifacts' for decades. While even the most advanced computer scientists are still discovering new kinds of Deep Learning and GAN artifacts in the simplist of cases.
Conversely what does the GAN do if there is NO contrast? Answer : IDK, would depend on your algo.
I don’t disagree, that’s why I made that qualified statement. My perspective goes back to SMOTE - which as an augmentation appears to work well (but not as well as other things).
Thought experiment: suppose we have a GAN for enhancing MRIs with low dose of contrast agent. What does the GAN do if the contrast agent is so delayed that only part of the brain recieves contrast?

(FD: also lacking GAN experience, hence my statement about being open to being convinced) With augmentation, we can always refer back to performance on real-world cases. If generated images are used in the clinic, we should be very wary about whether the details we see are real.

OK, IMHO & based on my research (FD: less exp w/GAN’s) this very similar to a super resolution algorithm with a VAE/GAN. I’m almost more concerned about augmentation role than this. Why do you differ in opinion?
BIG difference between using GANs to synthesize new cases for training (whether of rads or algorithms) using them to ‘enhance’ images for clinical interpretation.

I agree, but as with all things in DL, it is dependent not only on algorithm but substrate data. (Cc: @JasonKnapp39 ). @KheironMedical seemed to do a nice job with its GAN, so I’m hopeful for Subtle. Rapid approval part of @SGottliebFDA ‘s FDA #AI policies.
